-- 
U.K. Business Insolvency Rate Dropped in June, Experian Says

-- B y   N i d a a   B a k h s h
-- 
2011-07-17T23:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-17/u-k-business-insolvency-rate-dropped-in-june-experian-says.html
The number of large and medium-sized
U.K. businesses becoming insolvent fell in June, according to
data compiled by  Experian Plc (EXPN) , a global information services
company.  The rate of failure for businesses with 101 to 500
employees dropped to 0.08 percent last month from 0.17 percent a
year earlier, the Dublin-based company said today in an e-mailed
statement. The failure rate at businesses employing 51 to 100
workers declined to 0.19 percent from 0.23 percent.  The south west of the U.K. had the lowest rate of
insolvency with 0.07 percent of businesses failing, according to
the statement. The number of insolvencies in the north west and
 Scotland  increased.  The building-materials industry had the highest failure
rate at 0.27 percent, followed by the  construction industry  with
0.18 percent, the statement said.  The failure rate for all U.K. businesses was unchanged at
0.09 percent, the statement said. The financial-strength score
fell to 80.06 percent from 80.83 percent in June last year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Nidaa Bakhsh in London at 
 nbakhsh@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
